(143,1,'2024-01-23 20:30:20','2024-01-23 20:30:20','<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"right\",\"id\":86,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image alignright size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/AdobeStock_142610858-1024x684.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-86\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Software development freelancing...</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many locations around the globe that are hotspots for software development.   If you happen to live in one of those places, jobs can come looking for you.   But there are many places around the world that have little or no jobs in this field.  In those places you need some extra skills to get and keep work, but it can be done.  This site is a place to find help and to build community of fellow developers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Welcome</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My intention with this main page is to tell a story of a journey that you might be on.  I\'ll try to keep it pretty brief and include \"Learn more...\" links so you can dive deeper as you need.   Hopefully you will find yourself on this journey and find where you are in the story.  When you do, I invite you to contact me.  My intention is that I can help guide you along.   I hope that this will become a community of like minded people.  I invite you to help me understand your needs and together we will keep you moving.  No tricks or fees are involved.   See my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"22\">About page</a> for that background.  If you have questions or comments along the way please email me.   This site is a work in progress and I intend to develop it to meet the needs of my readers. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Developing your skills</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While traditional full time employment brings a degree of long term job security, freelancers need to keep their current skills fresh in order to stay relevant.  High tech work is constantly changing with new fields opening up almost daily.  Those new fields often have a higher demand for skilled individuals.  Being willing and able to add new leading edge skills will increase your chances to find work and will often pay much better.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Front end web</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The World Wide Web is a rapidly evolving place, and it is a challenging field to stay fresh in.   Sometimes there are dramatic shifts in interactive tech.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/front-end-web/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"49\">Learn more...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Back end web</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Back end technologies don\'t change as fast as front end, but...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/back-end-web/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"52\">Learn more...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Full stack</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the surface full stack development is just front end and back end, but there is more to consider...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/full-stack/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"55\">Learn more...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Working globally</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the advent of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open-source_software\"><strong>open-source software</strong></a> there arose the need to have world wide access to the source code for the many projects.   <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git\"><strong>Git</strong></a> is the source control tool invented for Linux development.  <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GitHub\"><strong>GitHub</strong></a> is a web interface for software development which uses Git for the source control features, and describes itself as collaborative version control.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>GitHub</strong> supports the creation of personal accounts.  Each account can contain a number of repositories, which can be made public or private access.   A personal account allows a developer to create a repository for each project that is being worked on.   On the developer\'s personal machine, a matching copy of the GitHub repository can be made in a process called cloning.   As work progresses on the local machine and certain testable milestones are reached, the local changes can be committed and pushed to the GitHub repository.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get an idea of how this looks visit <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\">my GitHub account.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using a GitHub account with repositories for each project that you have done allows others (if your repo is public) to see not only your code and documentation, but also the process you used to make the changes.   Each time you fix a bug or add a new feature, you should push that to GitHub with a comment that describes the fix or new feature.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=59\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Learn more...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Building your brand</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/building-your-brand/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"76\">Learn more...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Finding work</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a number of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freelancer\">freelance</a> marketplaces online.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.upwork.com/freelance-jobs/\">Upwork</a> is one we recommend.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/finding-work/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"79\">Learn more...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Latest Posts</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:latest-posts {\"align\":\"center\"} /-->','Home','','inherit','closed','closed','','2-revision-v1','','','2024-01-23 20:30:20','2024-01-23 20:30:20','',2,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=143',0,'revision','',0),
(147,1,'2024-02-03 00:41:08','2024-02-03 00:41:08','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are plenty of resources to learn full stack skills.  Just see Wikipedia\'s \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontend_and_backend\">Frontend and backend</a>\" page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While it seems obvious that full stack includes both front end and back end skills there is more to it.   The most obvious is the issue of deployment and configuration.  After all the front end (web page) needs to know how to connect to the back end server.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fortunately, there are many cloud platforms that provide all of these services and integration and deployment into a simple \"one click\" service.    This WordPress site is running on a single core, Cloudways VPS (virtual private server) in a <a href=\"https://www.vultr.com\">Vultr </a>datacenter in Seattle, Washington.   In fact that VPS hosts several WordPress sites as well as other technologies I am playing with. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have chosen to focus on using WordPress because:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It is free</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It is open source</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It is widely used (43% of all websites on the internet use WP)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It is very flexible since it is a general website builder, a content management system, and a blogging platform all rolled into one. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It is fairly easy to use</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It is the platform I am using to build this site</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It allows me to train new developers in this field by having them help me improve and expand this site.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For more information on the benefits of WordPress read the article <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/why-you-should-use-wordpress/\">6 Most Important Reasons to Use WordPress in 2024</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Full stack','','inherit','closed','closed','','55-revision-v1','','','2024-02-03 00:41:08','2024-02-03 00:41:08','',55,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=147',0,'revision','',0),
(148,1,'2024-02-09 23:07:35','2024-02-09 23:07:35','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">GitHub</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the advent of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open-source_software\"><strong>open-source software</strong></a> there arose the need to have world wide access to the source code for the many projects.   <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git\"><strong>Git</strong></a> is the source control tool invented for Linux development.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are command line versions of git for all major desktop systems.  One of the more popular graphical interfaces for git is <a href=\"https://desktop.github.com\"><strong>GitDesktop</strong></a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GitHub\"><strong>GitHub</strong></a> is a web interface for software development which uses Git for the source control features, and describes itself as collaborative version control.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>GitHub</strong> supports the creation of personal accounts.  Each account can contain a number of repositories, which can be made public or private access.   A personal account allows a developer to create a repository for each project that is being worked on.   On the developer\'s personal machine, a matching copy of the GitHub repository can be made in a process called cloning.   As work progresses on the local machine and certain testable milestones are reached, the local changes can be committed and pushed to the GitHub repository.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get an idea of how this looks visit <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\">my GitHub account.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using a GitHub account with repositories for each project that you have done allows others (if your repo is public) to see not only your code and documentation, but also the process you used to make the changes.   Each time you fix a bug or add a new feature, you should push that to GitHub with a comment that describes the fix or new feature.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Capture your learning in a repository.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many tutorial sites to help you learn new skills.  As an example look at <strong><a href=\"https://www.frontendmentor.io\">Frontend Mentor.</a></strong>  This site is helpfully setup to capture your work for each challenge in a GitHub repository.  While it seems natural to download the starting material and jump right into the work, resist this urge and be very intentional in utilizing the features of Git.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you begin a challenge, you should </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create a new repository to house it.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Download the initial codebase provided, and push that to GitHub as your starting point.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Take the first step in the challenge, then test it, and finally push that work.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Test all the features you have done so far during the challenge.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>If you find a bug or perhaps a new feature or enhancement, stop and create an issue in the repository.   You don\'t have to fix it immediately, but it is very important to record the issue and steps to reproduce it.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Continue your work stepwise capturing each step by pushing it with a descriptive comment.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Finally, or during the course of your work, look at the outstanding issues and pick one or two to address.  As each is fixed push the fix and close the issue. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you are all finished with the challenge, take the time to create a ReadMe file in the repository.   In the first paragraph, and prominently marked, describe the specific skills demonstrated.  For instance if you are learning new HTML5 multimedia tags, list those.   This will be important when you start looking for work.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, update your resumé, CV, or Upwork profile to have a link to that repository.  A prospect client reading your profile will be able to click on that and see a clear demonstration that you actually do know that specific skill.    One final note is that when you do a real project of your own design,  replace the link to the challenge repository with a link to your own original project repository.   Putting your skills to work on a project of your own design shows that you really know how and why to use that skill.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Create a project with other developers.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you learn with your friends take the opportunity to propose an original project that you all can work on together.   Get a consensus of the scope and focus of the project, but feel free to include some features that require a skill that only a few collaborators know well.   This teaches the real world reality that open-source software is a collaboration of many people to build and enhance projects that no single person can achieve alone. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Search GitHub for a project that you are interested in learning more about it. </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Take some time to browse the galaxy of open-source projects in GitHub and find ones that you know about, or are interested in learning about.   You can actively follow the work of others, and can review the code that has been pushed to see how it has been coded.    Clone the repository to your local machine so you have a working copy.  As you test it out and find bugs or desired features, consider creating an issue in the GitHub project.   Note that some repositories have restrictions about who can do what.   By following projects, you will learn.  As you submit features, and if you get a chance to fix an issue you will start building your public credentials.   When you do that, be sure to update your resumé or CV or profile to point the projects you have participated in.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Work globally...','','inherit','closed','closed','','59-revision-v1','','','2024-02-09 23:07:35','2024-02-09 23:07:35','',59,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=148',0,'revision','',0),
(149,1,'2024-02-10 22:01:14','2024-02-10 22:01:14','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because of the rapid pace of technology development and market requirements, most web and application development is done by integrated teams.  No one person can do it all themselves. It takes a team of specialists working individually and cross discipline to be successful. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Some of the roles that are needed are:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Project lead</strong> - responsible for planning how the individuals in the team can work together to complete the project.   This is usually done in cooperation with the whole team to come to consensus on next steps and how to keep the project moving.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Design lead</strong> - responsible for the technical design and requirements for each major piece of the solution.   This person is responsible for making sure that the contribution of all the team members will fit together and produce a good product.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Database designer</strong> - much of the interface between the different parts of the solution are stored in a database.   This person designs the specific tables, columns, and indexes needed to ensure proper communication and integrity.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Lead coder</strong> - this coder is the lead and will establish and enforce coding standards and facilitate code reviews.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Coder</strong> - an individual contributor that writes one or more specific code components. They may be front end, back end, or full stack coders depending on the languages they are proficient in. They will also design and write functional tests that ensure proper operation. These tests are often referred to as <strong>unit tests</strong> because they test the function of a specific code module.    </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Tester</strong> - a person responsible for designing an implementing test suites that ensure that the individual code components operate together.   This person will often work with the individual coders to ensure their unit tests are properly written.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Documenter</strong> - works with the individual team members to understand how their contributions work and writes functional internal documentation and/or end user documentation.  The documentation may be in the form of a user manual but will also likely have on screen components such as roll-over tool tips or info links like ⓘ.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Source controller</strong> - ensures that all of the artifacts of the team members are properly kept in a repository and that all changes to those artifacts are also captured in the repository.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_engineering\">Software engineering</a> team processes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Requirements_analysis\">Requirements analysis</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Scope and effort estimation</strong> </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Prioritizing next steps and coordinating cadence and milestones</strong> - eg. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agile_software_development\">Agile</a> </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_review\">Code reviews</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integration_testing\">Integration testing</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Test_automation\">Test automation</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_integration\">Continuous integration</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_deployment\">Software deployment</a></strong> - </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_tool\">Team tools</a></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The team processes are often facilitated by specialized software.  Here is a list of some of those.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repository_(version_control)\"><strong>Project repository manager</strong></a> - eg. GitHub</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_reviewing_software\"><strong>Code review software</strong></a> - eg. <a href=\"https://www.gerritcodereview.com/index.html\">Gerrit</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Bug, feature, and project management system</strong> - eg. <a href=\"https://www.atlassian.com/software/jira\">Jira</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_unit_testing_frameworks\"><strong>Unit testing framework</strong></a> - eg. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selenium_(software)\">Selenium</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Source, build, testing and deployment automation system</strong> - eg. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jenkins_(software)\">Jenkins</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_integration\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Continuous integration system</strong></a> - eg. GitHub Actions</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Deployment framework</strong> - eg. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kubernetes\">Kubernetes</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Build your brand</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best way to build your skills as a team player and move up to more responsible positions is to find a role that you can already fill and join a team.   With a little effort you will be able to learn more about the other team members and their roles as well as learn more about the larger project.   As you develop your skills you can build a reputation of trust.   Open source software projects are a great opportunity because they depend on volunteer contributions.  But, it should be noted that all work done for open software projects is not done for free.  The companies or organizations that rely on open source software often have specific needs that are not necessarily shared by the community at large.   These organizations will often pay their employees, or outside developers, to work on their special needs.  A close friend of mine does exactly this at SAS where I retired from. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many open source projects are dependent on other open source projects.  Working on one can give you valuable skills and understanding that can be a gateway to other projects.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, you can build relationships with other developers and learn of other opportunities.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Working in a team','','publish','closed','closed','','working-in-a-professional-team','','','2024-05-17 10:21:02','2024-05-17 10:21:02','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=149',0,'page','',0),
