(303,1,'2024-03-30 17:47:37','2024-03-30 17:47:37','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From his review of my Frontend page:  <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/your-front-end-development-journey-a-step-by-step-roadmap/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"299\">Your Front-End Development Journey: A Step-by-Step Roadmap</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Philemon\'s contributions','','inherit','closed','closed','','294-revision-v1','','','2024-03-30 17:47:37','2024-03-30 17:47:37','',294,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=303',0,'revision','',0),
(304,1,'2024-03-30 17:49:08','2024-03-30 17:49:08','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note:  This is also available as a <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Philemons-Front-End-Development-road-map.pdf\">downloadable PDF</a> for your use.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The world of web development is vast and exciting, and front-end development is at the forefront of creating user experiences that are both beautiful and functional. If you\'re looking to embark on a career as a front-end developer, this roadmap will guide you through the essential skills and technologies you need to master.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Phase 1: Building the Foundation</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Big Three:</strong> This journey starts with the fundamentals – HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>HTML:</strong>&nbsp;The building blocks of web pages, HTML structures content and defines the overall layout.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>CSS:</strong>&nbsp;Responsible for styling and visual presentation, CSS brings your web pages to life with colors, fonts, and layouts.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>JavaScript:</strong>&nbsp;The language that adds interactivity to web pages, allowing for animations, user input handling, and dynamic content.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Master the Basics:</strong>&nbsp;Focus on getting comfortable with the core functionalities of each language. Practice writing clean and well-structured code.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Phase 2: Deepening Your Skillset</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Going Beyond the Basics:</strong> Once you have a solid foundation, delve deeper into advanced concepts in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>HTML:</strong>&nbsp;Learn about semantic HTML, forms, and web components.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>CSS:</strong>&nbsp;Explore advanced CSS topics like preprocessors (SASS, LESS), responsive design for different screen sizes, and CSS frameworks (Bootstrap, Tailwind CSS).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>JavaScript:</strong>&nbsp;Master object-oriented programming concepts, understand the Document Object Model (DOM), and explore asynchronous programming with promises or async/await.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Version Control with Git:</strong>&nbsp;Learn Git, a version control system, to manage your code effectively and collaborate with others on projects.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Phase 3: Expanding Your Horizons</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Frontend Frameworks:</strong> Dive into popular front-end frameworks that streamline development and provide pre-built components. Popular choices include React, Angular, and Vue.js.<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Benefits:</strong>&nbsp;Frameworks offer faster development, reusable components, and a structured approach to building complex web applications.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>JavaScript Libraries:</strong>&nbsp;Explore powerful JavaScript libraries that enhance your development capabilities. Examples include jQuery (DOM manipulation), Axios (making HTTP requests), and Lodash (utility functions).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Build Projects:</strong>&nbsp;The best way to solidify your learning is by building projects. Start with small, personal projects and gradually progress to larger, more complex applications. This hands-on experience is invaluable for your portfolio.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Phase 4: Continuous Learning and Growth</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Stay Updated:</strong>&nbsp;The web development landscape is constantly evolving. Keep yourself updated with the latest trends and technologies by following industry blogs, attending conferences, and participating in online communities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Soft Skills:</strong>&nbsp;While technical skills are crucial, don\'t neglect soft skills like communication, collaboration, and problem-solving. These will be essential when working in a team environment.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Network and Build Your Portfolio:</strong>&nbsp;Connect with other developers, build a strong online presence, and showcase your work on a portfolio website.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Your Front-End Development Journey: A Step-by-Step Roadmap','','inherit','closed','closed','','299-revision-v1','','','2024-03-30 17:49:08','2024-03-30 17:49:08','',299,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=304',0,'revision','',0),
(306,1,'2024-03-30 17:51:38','2024-03-30 17:51:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From his review of my Frontend page:  <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/your-front-end-development-journey-a-step-by-step-roadmap/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"299\">Your Front-End Development Journey: A Step-by-Step Roadmap</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Philemon\'s contributions','','inherit','closed','closed','','294-revision-v1','','','2024-03-30 17:51:38','2024-03-30 17:51:38','',294,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=306',0,'revision','',0),
(307,1,'2024-03-30 17:52:18','2024-03-30 17:52:18','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the contributors to this site.  I am very grateful to their contributions:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/philemons-contributions/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"294\">Bahati Philemon</a> is one of my first readers. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Contributors','','inherit','closed','closed','','295-revision-v1','','','2024-03-30 17:52:18','2024-03-30 17:52:18','',295,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=307',0,'revision','',0),
(308,1,'2024-03-30 17:56:32','2024-03-30 17:56:32','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Front end, or<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Front-end_web_development\"> front-end web development</a> refers to the skills and technology related to building pages and applications that run in a web browser.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Skills</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a number of skills to learn in order to be a typical web designer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Almost all of them can be learned at a number of mentor sites.  One of which is <a href=\"https://www.frontendmentor.io\">FrontendMentor</a>.  That site (and others like it) have a wealth of information and tutorials that teach you the fundamentals and details of all of these skills.   After reading this page and exploring FrontendMentor some, I recommend you try one of their challenges yourself.     </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another frontend learning site that is recommended is <a href=\"https://www.freecodecamp.org\">freeCodeCamp</a>.  It not only has many good learning resources but it offers some significant certifications that will show what you have learned and practiced to potential employers or clients. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Looking ahead, in our page on <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally…</a> there is a challenge to do one of the FrontendMentor challenges and capture your process and final work in a GitHub repository that you can show off what you have learned.   Keep an eye out for that, as it is a very important step in your professional development. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML - Hyper Text Markup Language</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML\">HTML</a> is a rich markup language which can be viewed and coded in a simple text editing program.   It consists of the text to be presented interspersed with HTML markup tags that specify how that text should be displayed.   The filename usually ends in either .htm or .html to indicated that it can be displayed in a web browser.  The HTML markup standards have been around since the beginning of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web\">World Wide Web.</a>  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML5</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML5\">HTML5</a> is simply the 5th major revision of the HTML standards that added significant modern features that make some web pages very dynamic. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">CSS - Cascading Style Sheets</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CSS\">CSS</a> is a speciality language for styling text and graphics.   While simple HTML can be coded to create the desired look and layout it can be extremely tedious to do so on a large scale.   If you are not consistent then the look and feel will be inconsistent.  Furthermore, if you decide to change the way your site looks then you will have a monstrous job to adjust all of the tags from start to finish.   The intent of CSS is that the raw HTML page should contain the content only.   A single reference in the header of the page is made to a .css file that contains the styling directives.   If you choose to change the look and feel, then you can code a new css file and change the reference to point to the new one.    A further refinement of that idea is with a content management system (CMS) that stores the content in a database.  But, that is another subject for another day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">JavaScript - A procedural programming language for web pages.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Javascript\">JavaScript</a> is a programming language inspired by Java that is meant to run inside a web page.   All of the actual work is performed by the web browser itself. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As discussed above, all of the above technologies can run on any computer with a web browser.  The HTML, CSS files and any embedded JavaScript code can be contained in a text file in a folder on the local computer.   You can test this yourself by creating a simple web page in a text editor (Notepad or TextEdit) and storing it on your hard drive.  Cut and paste this in your favorite text editor into a file called HelloWorld.htm:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;HTML&gt;\n&lt;H1&gt;Hello World!&lt;/H1&gt;\n&lt;/HTML&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then using your file browser (Windows explorer or Mac Finder) to locate that file and open it as you would any other document. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTTP - Hypertext Transport Protocol</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes, that is all that is needed.  However, that does not make any use of the internet or the World Wide Web.   The \"World Wide\" part of the Web indicates that computers all over the world that are connected to the internet can work together to present a very dynamic universe of information and entertainment.    In order to connect your local computer to any web page in the World Wide Web you simply enter a web address such as <a href=\"http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm\">http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm</a> into the search or address bar of your browser.  The formal name for this address is a URL.  See the wikipedia page <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/URL\">A&nbsp;<strong>uniform resource locator</strong>&nbsp;(<strong>URL</strong>)</a> for details.  The first four characters stand for HyperText Transport Protocol which is one of several protocols as explained in the URL page.  After that the \':\' indicates the beginning of the location of the resource which usually starts with \'//\' followed by the name of the resource.   Try it yourself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What happened when you pressed return after that address is that your browser used that resource information to find the appropriate web server somewhere in the world (MichaelKentBurns.com) and request a specific page (HelloWorld.htm).  A web server program running on that computer located the file for that page and other associated information and sent it back to your browser running on your computer.  Your browser then formatted it according to the HTML rules and you then see the results.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If, however, you have saved a web page on your local hard drive you would access it using the \'file\' protocol with an address something like this: \"<a>file://C:/Michael/HelloWorld.htm</a>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The details of that is for the next page (<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/back-end-web/\">Back end web</a>).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Before you move on, remember this roadmap to your career</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A friend of mine who is a reader of this site has contributed a <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/philemons-contributions/your-front-end-development-journey-a-step-by-step-roadmap/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"299\">roadmap to a Front-End development journey</a>.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Front end web','','inherit','closed','closed','','49-revision-v1','','','2024-03-30 17:56:32','2024-03-30 17:56:32','',49,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=308',0,'revision','',0),
(309,1,'2024-04-01 20:14:29','2024-04-01 20:14:29','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From his review of my Frontend page:  <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/your-front-end-development-journey-a-step-by-step-roadmap/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"299\">Your Front-End Development Journey: A Step-by-Step Roadmap</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Philemon\'s contributions','','inherit','closed','closed','','294-revision-v1','','','2024-04-01 20:14:29','2024-04-01 20:14:29','',294,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=309',0,'revision','',0),
(310,1,'2024-04-01 20:24:12','2024-04-01 20:24:12','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Philemon Bahati has been a friend for over a year now and I had the pleasure of meeting him in person in April/May 2023 in Bukavu, DR Congo where he lives.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He has been actively reviewing this site and taking on challenges.   During his reviews he has made  a number of recommendations and authored some significant contributions.    In recognition of that, I am now officially adding him to my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"295\">contributors page</a>.   Please welcome him and be sure to visit his <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/philemons-contributions/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"294\">contributions page</a>.   I\'m sure there will be new material there soon.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His first contribution is available on his contributions page and is referenced from the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/front-end-web/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"49\">front end web</a> page.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Post 2: Welcome a new contributor: Philemon','','publish','open','open','','welcome-a-new-contributor-philemon','','','2024-06-02 19:55:08','2024-06-02 19:55:08','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=310',0,'post','',0),
(311,1,'2024-04-01 20:24:12','2024-04-01 20:24:12','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Philemon Bahati has been a friend for over a year now and I had the pleasure of meeting him in person in April/May 2023 in Bukavu, DR Congo where he lives.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He has been actively reviewing this site and taking on challenges.   During his reviews he has made  a number of recommendations and authored some significant contributions.    In recognition of that, I am now officially adding him to my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"295\">contributors page</a>.   Please welcome him and be sure to visit his <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/philemons-contributions/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"294\">contributions page</a>.   I\'m sure there will be new material there soon.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His first contribution is available on his contributions page and is referenced from the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/front-end-web/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"49\">front end web</a> page.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Welcome a new contributor: Philemon','','inherit','closed','closed','','310-revision-v1','','','2024-04-01 20:24:12','2024-04-01 20:24:12','',310,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=311',0,'revision','',0),
(316,1,'2024-04-16 21:47:39','2024-04-16 21:47:39','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the contributors to this site.  I am very grateful to their contributions:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/philemons-contributions/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"294\">Bahati Philemon</a> is one of my first readers. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>ASHUZA Destin is one of my first readers. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Contributors','','inherit','closed','closed','','295-revision-v1','','','2024-04-16 21:47:39','2024-04-16 21:47:39','',295,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=316',0,'revision','',0),
(317,7,'2024-04-16 21:54:06','2024-04-16 21:54:06','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Destin has done excellent work reviewing and recommending improvements to the pages of this site. He has completed our  <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/full-stack/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"55\">full stack page</a> with his recommendations and also those from Philemon and Efatha.   I\'m confident there will be more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":397,\"width\":\"554px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/ash-picture-1024x875.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-397\" style=\"width:554px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><br>Hello! I\'m <strong>ASHUZA Destin</strong>, a tech enthusiast with a particular passion for development, especially in applications and websites. I\'m primarily focused on backend development, specializing in the PHP programming language, particularly with the Laravel framework. However, I also have some knowledge in frontend development, including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and Bootstrap. <a href=\"https://github.com/AshDest\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://github.com/AshDest\">My github</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','ASHUZA Destin\'s contributions','','publish','closed','closed','','ashuza-destins-contributions','','','2024-06-02 21:32:27','2024-06-02 21:32:27','',295,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=317',0,'page','',0),
(318,1,'2024-04-16 21:54:06','2024-04-16 21:54:06','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Destin has done excellent work reviewing and recommending improvements to the pages of this site.   He will be editing our <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/full-stack/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"55\">full stack page</a> with his recommendations and also those from Philemon and Efatha. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','ASHUZA Destin\'s contributions','','inherit','closed','closed','','317-revision-v1','','','2024-04-16 21:54:06','2024-04-16 21:54:06','',317,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=318',0,'revision','',0),
(319,1,'2024-04-16 21:54:46','2024-04-16 21:54:46','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the contributors to this site.  I am very grateful to their contributions:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/philemons-contributions/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"294\">Bahati Philemon</a> is one of my first readers. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/ashuza-destins-contributions/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"317\">ASHUZA Destin</a> is one of my first readers. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Contributors','','inherit','closed','closed','','295-revision-v1','','','2024-04-16 21:54:46','2024-04-16 21:54:46','',295,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=319',0,'revision','',0),
(322,1,'2024-04-17 22:44:02','2024-04-17 22:44:02','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>As mentioned in the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally page</a>, GitHub is an excellent way to keep a repository of a software project. A WordPress site is no exception. However, a WordPress site is significantly different than normal software projects in several regards:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\r\n<li>There is a lot of WordPress itself, as well as its Themes and Plugins that are contained in the public_html directory. That is OK, and it\'s worthwhile tracking changes to those files. For one, it is a good way to detect corruption in a site.</li>\r\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\r\n<li>The vast majority of the content of a WP site is in posts and pages. When an author writes a blog post or a page of any sort, it does not create any new web pages in public_html. This is a result of the fact that WP contains a powerful CMS (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Content_management_system\">ContentManagementSystem</a>). A CMS manages the content in a database not a directory full of fully rendered HTML pages. This is discussed more in the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/full-stack/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"55\">Full stack</a> page. The actual content of a blog post or a page is stored as a separate record in the wp_posts table. Blog posts have a post_type of \'post\' and pages (like this one) have a post_type of \'page\'. There are in fact a number of other things that get stored in the wp_posts table. As a result of these items stored as records in a table, doing the GitHub tracking of the text of a file will not show changes in individual posts or pages.</li>\r\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Because the main visible content is stored in a database table it is necessary to extract the individual records of the wp_posts (and other tables) to textual form so the normal GitHub mechanisms can show it in a readable form. As a first step to doing that, I have written a shells script called \'<strong>dumpall</strong>\' that is kept in the public_html directory (for now). That script is run in a shell process on the WP host site before a Git commit and push commands are run to update the GitHub repository. This is step 1 in the GitHub issue #10 of the GitHub repository\'. Later, I will write a program to extract each record of the wp_posts table into a separate text file in a .data/posts directory. It will require some nicer format than a simple SQL dump.</p>\r\n<p>One issue with the <strong>dumpall </strong>script is that the SQL dump for a specific table creates an INSERT statement to create all records into the table, but all of those records are written to a single line.  Thus when GitHub tries to show the differences between subsequent revisions of a file, it looks like one VERY long line with lots of differences.   What I would rather have is an INSERT statement that puts each record on a separate line.   I have written a shell alias that uses the sed command to split that INSERT line into many lines.   Thus, in the .data directory of my GitHub repository you will see the original SQL dump in a file named <strong>wp_posts.sql</strong> and a version with the lines split named <strong>wp_posts.split.sql</strong>.  I am pushing this change on Wednesday April 17th, 2024 so you should see the text of this post will be changed in the <strong>wp_posts.split.sql</strong> file.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','How to use GitHub to source control a WordPress site','','inherit','closed','closed','','266-revision-v1','','','2024-04-17 22:44:02','2024-04-17 22:44:02','',266,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=322',0,'revision','',0),
(324,4,'2024-04-17 23:25:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now have 2 other contributors (Philemon, and Ashuza Destin) who will be editing some pages and making some posts.  However, I\'ve never done these tasks as a contributor role.   I have logged in under a test user named Mike and find that I can create a new post, but not yet a page. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the dashboard I can see the Posts section, and I can obviously add a post (this one). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'m not sure how this is going to work.   I think if the Michael person will create a page for me as a contributor and change the author to Mike, I\'ll be able to edit that page and perhaps add new pages that are children of that.     Let\'s see if that works...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When I clicked the \'Publish\' button in this editor, I see that it is going to submit this for review (by Michael).   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','A test post from Mike as a contributor','','pending','open','open','','','','','2024-04-17 23:25:33','2024-04-17 23:25:33','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=324',0,'post','',0),
(325,4,'2024-04-17 23:24:38','2024-04-17 23:24:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We now have 2 other contributors (Philemon, and Ashuza Destin) who will be editing some pages and making some posts.  However, I\'ve never done these tasks as a contributor role.   I have logged in under a test user named Mike and find that I can create a new post, but not yet a page. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the dashboard I can see the Posts section, and I can obviously add a post (this one). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'m not sure how this is going to work.   I think if the Michael person will create a page for me as a contributor and change the author to Mike, I\'ll be able to edit that page and perhaps add new pages that are children of that.     Let\'s see if that works...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When I clicked the \'Publish\' button in this editor, I see that it is going to submit this for review (by Michael).   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','A test post from Mike as a contributor','','inherit','closed','closed','','324-autosave-v1','','','2024-04-17 23:24:38','2024-04-17 23:24:38','',324,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=325',0,'revision','',0),
(326,4,'2024-04-17 23:30:11','2024-04-17 23:30:11','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>I tried writing a post and it\'s in the pipe for review.</p>\r\n<p>\'Mike\' was not able to create or edit posts in his role as \'Contributor\', so Michael has now promoted him to Editor.  With that role, Mike needs to be very careful and only edit pages that he has been requested to.  There is a safety net since Michael uses Git to change track everything in this site and we can roll back revisions as needed.   </p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Mike as contributor test contributions','','publish','closed','closed','','mike-as-contributor-test-contributions','','','2024-04-17 23:50:12','2024-04-17 23:50:12','',295,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=326',0,'page','',0),
(327,1,'2024-04-17 23:30:11','2024-04-17 23:30:11','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I tried writing a post and it\'s in the pipe for review.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Mike as contributor test contributions','','inherit','closed','closed','','326-revision-v1','','','2024-04-17 23:30:11','2024-04-17 23:30:11','',326,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=327',0,'revision','',0),
