(503,1,'2024-06-29 20:01:16','2024-06-29 20:01:16','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I met these three guys during my first visit to Congo in May 2023.  I chose them for Cohort-1 because they were already well prepared and they are a good mix of technical abilities and experiences. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Jean Bahati Philemon</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":353,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/work-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-353\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Philémon</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I first had contact with Philémon about in 2022 when he was getting started on Upwork.  He is a true pioneer in this field.   I gave him some recommendations about what international clients will expect to see when evaluating web developers.  One of my recommendations was to get a GitHub account and start posting his work.  He jumped right on that and took off.   He not only has a 100% job success rating, but is also Top Rated.  When you see the <a href=\"https://support.upwork.com/hc/en-us/articles/211068468-Top-Rated\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Top Rated</a> badge on an Upwork profile, it means that person is considered to be in the top 10% of all Upwork users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not only is he a pioneer he is also a leader and mentor. He spends a fair amount of time encouraging and advising others who wish to follow in his footsteps.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His contributions to this site are shown on his <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/philemons-contributions/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"294\">contributions page.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Philémon is a Frontend Web Developer with 5+ years of experience in developing websites. He has a passion for creating user-friendly, visually appealing, and functional websites. My expertise lies in HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript, React js, Tailwind, and Bootstrap. He has a strong understanding of web standards and accessibility guidelines.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Github: <a href=\"https://github.com/bahati7\">https://github.com/bahati7</a><br>Upwork: <a href=\"https://www.upwork.com/freelancers/~01f54e6da3d373b5f2\">https://www.upwork.com/freelancers/~01f54e6da3d373b5f2</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Ashuza Destin</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":397,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/ash-picture-1024x875.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-397\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Ashuza </figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Hello! I’m <strong>ASHUZA Destin</strong>, a tech enthusiast with a particular passion for development, especially in applications and websites. I’m primarily focused on backend development, specializing in the PHP programming language, particularly with the Laravel framework. However, I also have some knowledge in frontend development, including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and Bootstrap. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/AshDest\">GitHub: https://github.com/AshDest</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Upwork: <a href=\"https://www.upwork.com/freelancers/~01c7a3ec16524a8602\">https://www.upwork.com/freelancers/~01c7a3ec16524a860</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ash has wide experience in full stack development and does excellent work.   <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/ashuza-destins-contributions/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"317\">His contributions page </a>for this site shows that he has made major editing and development of several of the pages.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Efatha Byamungu Rutakaza </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":496,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/IMG_2344-768x1024.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-496\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Screenshot</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Efatha is the least experienced of this group, but he more than makes up for that by being a very eager and enthusiastic student and worker.   He has learned some important aspects of working as part of a team, and others are wise to learn from him.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Staying updated, leveraging, networking, and follow all of the instructions.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Clear and consistent communication is essential, and realized that collaboration is far more productive than competition...\"    \"When team members support each other and share knowledge freely it creates a positive and productive work environment.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/971718809?badge=0\\u0026autopause=0\\u0026player_id=0\\u0026app_id=58479\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://player.vimeo.com/video/971718809?badge=0&amp;autopause=0&amp;player_id=0&amp;app_id=58479\n</div><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><a href=\"https://www.upwork.com/freelancers/~013a3c69f58b323c60\">Interview produced by Théophile Achiza</a></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Efatha says: \"I am an experienced Front-End Web Developer with a strong background in HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Bootstrap. I specialize in creating responsive, modern web templates, visually appealing websites and applications. Skilful in Figma for designing user-friendly interfaces, I bring a comprehensive approach to aesthetic excellence. Let\'s collaborate to bring your vision to life!\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Upwork: <a href=\"https://www.upwork.com/freelancers/~01f4543035bc52ff94\">https://www.upwork.com/freelancers/~01f4543035bc52ff94</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>GitHub: <a href=\"https://github.com/efatha/\">https://github.com/efatha/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Their work together</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These three have collaborated on a full stack solution that presents a selection of question/answer surveys.  Once completed and submitted, the results are written out in JSON file format and submitted to a backend server where the data is written to SQL tables.   The survey results can then be queried from the database and viewed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can try their demo on our demo server:  http://<a href=\"http://demo.michaelkentburns.com/dashboard/MKB/cohort1/MKB-cohort-1-Demo/\">demo.MichaelKentBurns.com</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>More important than the finished product is the code and process they used to build the demo.  You can view all that in the <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/MKB-cohort-1-Demo\">GitHub repository they used to do the work.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Cohort-1','','inherit','closed','closed','','494-revision-v1','','','2024-06-29 20:01:16','2024-06-29 20:01:16','',494,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=503',0,'revision','',0),
(505,1,'2024-06-29 20:12:56','2024-06-29 20:12:56','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Michael lives near Cedar Park, Texas with his wife Mary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"flexWrap\":\"nowrap\",\"justifyContent\":\"space-between\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":39,\"width\":\"309px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"aspectRatio\":\"1.3360655737704918\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/IMG_1613-1024x768.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-39\" style=\"aspect-ratio:1.3360655737704918;width:309px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":169,\"width\":\"324px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/MichaelAtWork-1024x768.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-169\" style=\"width:324px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Michael is a 40 year veteran software engineer.  The last 33 years was as a principal systems developer at <a href=\"http://www.sas.com\">SAS Institute</a>.  His main responsibility was the <a href=\"https://www.sas.com/en_us/search.html?q=metadata%20server\">enterprise metadata server</a> that connects all SAS products. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He is now happily retired, but not yet done with the field.  This site is home base for his new focus of mentoring programmers in the art of software engineering.   The main emphasis is individuals living in a places that do not have software development jobs.  This means that their best opportunity is to go freelance.   Doing so allows them to stay in their culture and home community.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While freelancing is a start, there are also opportunities to do so much more as part of a larger development team focused on many open source software projects.   This is something that I am moving into myself.  Join me.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Students and Contributors</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using the power of the internet and all the collaborative software available, I can now mentor and collaborate with like minded individuals around the globe. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Bukavu, Democratic Republic of the Congo </h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My first cohort of students live in the city of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bukavu\">Bukavu</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"textAlign\":\"center\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-text-align-center\">Cohort-1</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cohort-1 contains three guys that I met during my first visit to Congo in May 2023: <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/cohort-1/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"494\">See full details.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"linkTo\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped\"><!-- wp:image {\"id\":353,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/work-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-353\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Philémon</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":397,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/ash-picture-1024x875.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-397\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Ashuza </figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":358,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/Efatha.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-358\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Efatha</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"textAlign\":\"center\",\"level\":1,\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading has-text-align-center has-medium-font-size\"></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"textAlign\":\"center\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-text-align-center\">Cohort-2</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cohort-2 is about to launch.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The candidates for Cohort-2 are:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Théophile Achiza</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Gauthier Utukufu</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Samuel Bitingingwa</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Solomon Mwilo</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These candidates are all very new to web design and Upwork.  They will have to begin to develop the web development part of their Upwork profile as well as their GitHub repository.   It is important that they capture the projects they will build while learning web design so that they develop and demonstrate the professional skills needed to work effectively for clients.   Most web design students do their projects on their own personal computer in a directory where they write and test the code.  Then they hand in their work to the instructor for grading.    This is NOT how professional developers work or deliver their finished work. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As they learn and build projects that demonstrate that skill they will begin to add the skills and projects to their web design profile in Upwork.   Prospective clients who come upon their profile will see their advertised skills, but they want to see some evidence of that skill put to work.   Their profile and GitHub repository is where that will be evident.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can follow their progress by reading my blog posts.  Good skill and hard work guys! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Contributors</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am grateful to those who have read this site and made valuable contributions through feedback and contributed material. <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/about-michael/contributors/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"295\">See this full list.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:social-links -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-social-links\"><!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\",\"service\":\"github\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/michaelkentburns/?lipi=urn%3Ali%3Apage%3Ad_flagship3_feed%3B6Dj3E8auRSy51Ad%2BgA7N%2FQ%3D%3D\",\"service\":\"linkedin\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\",\"service\":\"mail\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:social-link {\"url\":\"https://www.facebook.com/michael.burns.906\",\"service\":\"facebook\"} /--></ul>\n<!-- /wp:social-links -->\n\n<!-- wp:social-links -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-social-links\"></ul>\n<!-- /wp:social-links -->','About us','','inherit','closed','closed','','22-revision-v1','','','2024-06-29 20:12:56','2024-06-29 20:12:56','',22,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=505',0,'revision','',0),
(506,1,'2024-06-29 20:31:09','2024-06-29 20:31:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cohort 1 is finishing up their demo project this next week.  You can see the results posted on their <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/cohort-1/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"494\">Cohort-1 page</a>.  Also on that page is a short profile for each of them.  Finally there is a short video interview of Efatha regarding his experience.   The video was shot and produced by Théophile who is one of the candidates for Cohort-2.  He did an excellent job, and Efatha showed his enthusiasm and eagerness as always.  This will I hope, be an encouragement to the next students.  Please check it out. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once they complete their demo they need to plan what they will do next.  Perhaps they will take on an independent project with a new Upwork client.   Stay tuned...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meanwhile I am beginning to kick off Cohort-2 with four guys that are new to web design and Upwork.   First I have to write an Upwork job and invite them to join.  Once they have made their decision, I will create a new Cohort-2 page where I will introduce them and describe what they will be doing.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of my hopes is that the Cohort-1 guys will spend part of their time coming along side the new cohort and encourage, advise, and review the work of the new team.  Their effort will be very beneficial both as a model of what success looks like and also as a practical guide and encouragement to keep going.   Eventually, I hope that as the more experienced team takes on new projects they will invite the new guys to join them on some collaborative projects.   That is really the best (only?) way to learn to be a professional developer.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As always, I ask that you please take a short minute to leave a comment below and let me know what you think.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Post 8: Cohort 1 wrapping up their demo and cohort 2 is being organized.','','publish','open','open','','post-8-cohort-1-wrapping-up-their-demo-and-cohort-2-is-being-organized','','','2024-06-29 20:31:09','2024-06-29 20:31:09','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=506',0,'post','',3),
(507,1,'2024-06-29 20:31:09','2024-06-29 20:31:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cohort 1 is finishing up their demo project this next week.  You can see the results posted on their <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/cohort-1/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"494\">Cohort-1 page</a>.  Also on that page is a short profile for each of them.  Finally there is a short video interview of Efatha regarding his experience.   The video was shot and produced by Théophile who is one of the candidates for Cohort-2.  He did an excellent job, and Efatha showed his enthusiasm and eagerness as always.  This will I hope, be an encouragement to the next students.  Please check it out. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once they complete their demo they need to plan what they will do next.  Perhaps they will take on an independent project with a new Upwork client.   Stay tuned...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meanwhile I am beginning to kick off Cohort-2 with four guys that are new to web design and Upwork.   First I have to write an Upwork job and invite them to join.  Once they have made their decision, I will create a new Cohort-2 page where I will introduce them and describe what they will be doing.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of my hopes is that the Cohort-1 guys will spend part of their time coming along side the new cohort and encourage, advise, and review the work of the new team.  Their effort will be very beneficial both as a model of what success looks like and also as a practical guide and encouragement to keep going.   Eventually, I hope that as the more experienced team takes on new projects they will invite the new guys to join them on some collaborative projects.   That is really the best (only?) way to learn to be a professional developer.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As always, I ask that you please take a short minute to leave a comment below and let me know what you think.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Post 8: Cohort 1 wrapping up their demo and cohort 2 is being organized.','','inherit','closed','closed','','506-revision-v1','','','2024-06-29 20:31:09','2024-06-29 20:31:09','',506,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=507',0,'revision','',0),
(509,1,'2024-07-02 16:00:17','2024-07-02 16:00:17','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Introductions</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Cherubala Gauthier</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":708,\"width\":\"456px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/IMG-20240626-WA0016-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-708\" style=\"width:456px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Gauthier</strong> has completed 6 of the 7 tasks in the introductory course and is working on the largest task which is building a GitHub project of his choosing.  You can see it <a href=\"https://github.com/ElGautinho/My-first-tutorial-project\">yourself on GitHub</a>.  One thing I like about his project is that it has an immediate application of organizing the efforts of other volunteers in the media group at his church. The visual style of his page is very cool and well layed out. It has a pleasant but subdued graphic in the background with a clear and well balanced form in the center. He has used some simple text entry fields, a multiple choice button group, a pulldown selector, a sequence of checkboxes and a larger text box for comments and suggestions. He has coded value validation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The primary purpose of this exercise is the use of GitHub projects.   His README.md file is thorough.   It has a small table of contents up front.  It describes the purpose of the project he is building, and a description of the process he is using to build the project.  He describes the tools and techniques he is using, and has a start of a list of the lessons he has learned so far in the project.     </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He is using the Issues list feature of the project to list the 13 major steps in his process so far.  Each issue has a short description, and he is including the issue number and a short description of each of the 18 commits.   This helps me as a reviewer to quickly understand the intent, design, and process as well as what each commit contained.     <strong>Well done Gauthier!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Samuel Bulangalizi</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":709,\"width\":\"345px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/IMG_3765-768x1024.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-709\" style=\"width:345px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Samuel\'s</strong> <a href=\"https://github.com/Samuel11s/My-first-tutorial-project\">project for Task 7 </a> has a nice README.md file.   He describes his objectives, the features of the page,  the technology he will use to achieve it.  He describes the process he will follow with a rough schedule.   In his list of requirements the first is to learn basic Javascript.   This was a problem in his plan to build this page because Javascript is a lot to learn.    This is a worthwhile endeavor but it will delay the completion of his project.   He has done well in using the Issues feature of GitHub.  There are 6 closed issues, four of which he created and two of which I added.   These 6 he has completed and closed them.   There are 3 issues remaining, one of which is learning Javascript.    When I review the 11 commits he has made to his code I notice that he has entered good descriptions which allows me as a reviewer to know what the commit was for without having to open each to understand.   <strong>The main point of this task </strong>was to learn how to use the features of a GitHub project to complete a project and I think Samuel has done a fine job of demonstrating that knowledge.   From what he has coded already I can see that he knows how to design and layout a page well.  Well done Samuel, you have learned this lesson and I\'m confident that you will complete your project when you have learned the required Javascript. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Salomon Mwilo</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":710,\"width\":\"382px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/PXL_20240905_095856292.SK-I-901x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-710\" style=\"width:382px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Salomon\'s</strong> <a href=\"https://github.com/Salomonmwilo/My-first-tutorial-project\">project for Task 7</a> shows good progress already.  He has created an array of floating cards in a grid-template container.  He has created some nice stylings that make the cards pop and use a variety of colors that allows the eye to clearly distinguish the individual cards.   The grid adapts nicely to changes in size of display and orientation.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Achiza Masirika Théophile</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":711,\"width\":\"450px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/PXL_20240422_1509557552-1024x748.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-711\" style=\"width:450px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">You are not alone in this.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will be engaging not only the material, but you will have a <strong>mentor</strong> who has been through the course.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For this course, we anticipate this pairing:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Efatha will mentor Salomon</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Philemon will mentor Gauthier</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ashuza will mentor Samuel</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>And Michael will mentor Theophile.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Starting Course</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The starting course is designed to familiarize the student with the training website and the people and processes involved.   By the end of this course you will know what is on the site and where to find what you are looking for.  You will gain a high level overview of the training you can expect from this site.  You will also know how to interact with the material, track your progress and get the help you need on your training journey.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each <strong>course</strong> is composed of a series of <strong>tasks</strong>.  These are like lessons in most learning sites but here we call them tasks because they prepare you to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Know</strong> some new technology and skill</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Find the tools and environment to<strong> try it out for yourself</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Demonstrate</strong> your new skill</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>And finally to <strong>get some feedback </strong>about it which will guide your future learning.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The coordination of doing these tasks while using <strong>Upwork time tracker</strong>, taking surveys, and tracking hours for these steps is pretty tricky.I’m sorry about that, but these things need to be done. While our process includes lots of communication tools, we must continue to be consistent with the <strong>Upwork</strong> process which is important for accountability for both the client and the talent.   You need to learn this skill well if you want to engage other clients, which is the purpose of this training.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you get confused or can’t follow a specific step, please use the <strong>Upwork</strong> message system to let me know so I, or your mentor, can walk you through it. If you get stuck where you can’t make progress, then include the word ‘<strong>STUCK!</strong>’ In your message. This administrative detail will get easer as you go along.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 1: Access the training site and this course.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto <strong>Upwork</strong> and find the contract for this job. Start your time tracker to indicate what task you are starting.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto <strong><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/\">https://MichaelKentBurns.com</a></strong> site. Find the <strong>Subscribe</strong> field in the menu and subscribe yourself.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use the search field to find your name.  That should lead you to this page (and possibly others).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Leave a comment on this page so we know you were here.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Update time tracker to say you are <strong>done with task 1</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 2: Read the main ‘Home’ page to see your journey.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Note the time and update Upwork time tracker to say you are <strong>starting task 2</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Read the ‘<strong>Home</strong>’ page carefully down to and including ‘<strong>Working globally’</strong> section keeping some notes along the way. (There will be a quiz)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Feel free always to leave comments on any pages and posts. It will make it easier for you and I to know you have read that page.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto&nbsp;<a href=\"https://demo.michaelkentburns.com/dashboard/MKB/cohort1/MKB-cohort-1-Demo\"><strong>https://demo.michaelkentburns.com/dashboard/MKB/cohort1/MKB-cohort-1-Demo</strong></a>, select the ‘<strong>Visit the Demo-json</strong>’ button and take the ‘<strong>read-home-part1</strong>’ survey and press the ‘<strong>submission</strong>’ button.&nbsp;&nbsp;Your answers will be captured in a json file which will appear below the ‘<strong>Submission</strong>’ button.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Finally, press the ‘<strong>Save Survey Results (JSON)</strong>’ link at the bottom.&nbsp;&nbsp;You should then see a dialog indicating ‘<strong>Survey results saved successfully!</strong>’&nbsp;&nbsp;Select ‘<strong>Close</strong>’.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You may also notice that the JSON file was downloaded to your downloads directory.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Save that for future reference.&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>NOTE:</strong> If you have problems with the survey app, take notes, do a screen capture, or whatever.   Then communicate that with your mentor.   They may need to help you, or you might have uncovered a bug or a possible enhancement.  Your mentor will make that decision and enter an issue in their project to make sure it is dealt with.  By the end of this starter course, you will know how to enter an issue yourself.   One step at a time.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Note the time and calculate how much time you have used for task 2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Then go to the time tracker and indicate you are done with task 2 and going on to task 3.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 3: Read the ‘About’ page.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Update time tracker that you are starting Task 3.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Read the ‘<strong>About</strong>’ page including the Cohort-1 section and the ‘<strong>See full details.</strong>’ page. When you read about <strong>Philémon</strong>, <strong>Ashuza</strong>, and <strong>Efatha</strong>, follow the links to their Github and Upwork profiles.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Take some time to study their Upwork profiles.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* On <strong>Philèmon’s profile</strong>, under his picture and ‘<strong>View profile</strong>’ notice that he has two specialized profiles.  Make a note of them and take a moment to notice how they are different than the main view of the profile.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* You will soon create your own specialized profile.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* The next section is ‘<strong>Work history</strong>’.  Take note of the various jobs he has done and the rating and comments for those.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> * Notice the ‘<strong>Portfolio</strong>’ section near the bottom of the profile.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Ashuza also has two specialized profiles: <strong>Full Stack</strong> and <strong>Mobile App</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Finally, notice their Certifications section. You will also get one or more certifications along the way.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* <strong>Ashuza’s GitHub profile</strong> shows that he has 40+ repositories! Many of them were created as he took online tutorials. Though some of those are fairly trivial, that is expected starting out.  You have to start somewhere, and now is that time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* What is important is that they demonstrate that he not only has badges claiming knowledge of languages, frameworks, and tools, he also has done a lot of visible work that shows that he spent considerable time learning and doing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You should remember that and make a practice of capturing all of your learning projects in your GitHub.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* We will talk more about that later.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* When you look at <strong>Efatha’s GitHub profile</strong> notice the section labeled ‘<strong>Contribution activity</strong>’. It indicates that he has recently worked on two repositories of his own, but also the ‘MKB-cohort-1-Demo’. If you click ‘<strong>Show more activity</strong>’ a few times, you will see his contributions to this training site.  As you go through this training you will be demonstrating your active work on a real world project.   That is what prospective clients will be looking for to know you are not just book learners.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Under the ‘<strong>Their work together</strong>’ section, you will read about the survey app you will be using.  That is the result of their demo project.  There is a direct link to that survey app and also a link to the GitHub repository they worked on.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, return to finish the ‘<strong>About</strong>’ page.  Find yourself in <strong>Cohort-2</strong> section, and read that section and this <strong>Cohort-2 </strong>page as well very carefully. Take notes of any questions you have.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. The final section of the \'<strong>About</strong>\' page: Read the <strong>contributors</strong> section and the pages it links to.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you get to the individual contributions pages notice that they have both edited and/or written several pages for this site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. Go to the survey app (see Task 2, step 4) and take the ‘<strong>read-about</strong>’ survey.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. Update time tracker that you have finished task 3.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 4: Read the Front end web page.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Update time tracker as usual starting task 4.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Using the table of contents on the site, go read the ‘<strong>Front end web</strong>’ page. Read it carefully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. As you read, make note for each section, whether you already know that information well, what you know a little bit, and what sections are new to you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. In the areas you don’t know well, take some time to follow some of the many links provided. Don’t study them in detail, but read enough to see what is discussed and what you may want to revisit at a later date.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. In the section about HTML and the Hello World page, take the time to actually try that for yourself. In the browser notice the address bar of your browser that the url uses the ‘<a href=\"file://\'/\">file://\'</a>protocol.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. When you get to the HTTP section, read that closely to understand how visiting a we page via http:// is different from file://</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>7 When you are done with task 4, take the survey ‘read-front-end-web -page’. You will be asked there to relate some of the notes you talk when reading this page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>8. Leave a comment at the bottom of the page and indicate something you learned on that page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>9. Update time tracker to indicate you are done with task 4.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 5:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Read ‘Back end web’ page.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Start your timekeeping as usual.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. In the introduction paragraphs make note of the two key differences between the Front end, and the Back end.  The differences have to do with the programs involved and where those programs run. Make sure you can briefly explain those differences.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Read the wikipedia page on \'Frontend and backend\'. See if you can learn what \'client side\' and \'server side\' mean and which programs run in each.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. Read the wikipedia page on LAMP.  See if you can find the \'Stack\' concept in the illustrations and make a list of what is in the stack.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. In the \'Key Components\' section notice some of the programming languages that can be used and identify which languages you already know something about.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. Pay attention to the section on \'Frameworks\' and research one of those frameworks enough to know why it would be used.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>7. In the \'Essential Skills...\' section, note which of those skills you think you should begin learning, and why?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>8. In the \'Common Tools and Technologies\' section, are there any tools you already know something about.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>9. In the \'Best Practices\' section, follow the link on \'Code Reviews\' and note two of the benefits of code reviews that would help you most at this time. You will be doing some code reviews with your mentor very soon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>10. Take the survey named <strong>Read-backend</strong>, and finish your time accounting. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 6:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Read ‘Full stack’ page.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Start your timekeeping as usual.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2.  The Full stack page covers the concepts of front end and back end, but at a higher level.  This page emphasizes the expert level of knowledge needed to bring all of the front end and back end skills together to make a full web based application.   At your level of learning, you are not expected to gain this knowledge, but it is important that you are aware that someone has to put it all together.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. What the Full stack page does not yet tell you is the importance of security.  We are just now starting to explore security issues in the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/security/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"583\">Security page</a> and some blog posts discussed there.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. Although this page leads to many other technologies to create full stack solutions, it also points out that for many purposes WordPress is a full stack solution that is open source and contains more advanced technologies that are available.  This is why I (Michael) chose WordPress to build this training site.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. Spend some time on this page just to be familiar with it, and return to it later when you have advanced in both front end and back end development and are ready to take on more.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. Take the \'<strong>read-full-stack</strong>\' survey, then finish up your time keeping. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 7:&nbsp;&nbsp;Read ‘Work globally’ page and take the two challenges it mentions.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You should now have taken challenges 1 through 4. If not, then do so now.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Cohort-2','','publish','open','closed','','cohort-2','','','2024-10-01 23:01:48','2024-10-01 23:01:48','',22,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=509',0,'page','',4),
(510,1,'2024-07-02 16:00:17','2024-07-02 16:00:17','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Introductions</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">You are not alone in this.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will be engaging not only the material, but you will have a <strong>mentor</strong> who has been through the course.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For this course, we anticipate this pairing:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Efatha will mentor Salomon</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Philemon will mentor Gauthier</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ashuza will mentor Samuel</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>And Michael will mentor Theophile.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Starting Course</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The starting course is designed to familiarize the student with the training website and the people and processes involved.   By the end of this course you will know what is on the site and where to find what you are looking for.  You will gain a high level overview of the training you can expect from this site.  You will also know how to interact with the material, track your progress and get the help you need on your training journey.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each <strong>course</strong> is composed of a series of <strong>tasks</strong>.  These are like lessons in most learning sites but here we call them tasks because they prepare you to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Know some new technology and skill</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Give you the tools and environment to try it out for yourself</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Demonstrate your new skill</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>And finally to get some feedback about it which will guide your future learning.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The coordination of doing these tasks while using Upwork time tracker, taking surveys, and tracking hours for these steps is pretty tricky.  I’m sorry about that, but these things need to be done.   While our process includes lots of communication tools, we must continue to be consistent with the <strong>Upwork</strong> process which is important for accountability for both the client and the talent.   You need to learn this skill well if you want to engage other clients, which is the purpose of this training.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you get confused or can’t follow a specific step, please use the <strong>Upwork</strong> message system to let me know so I, or your mentor, can walk you through it.     This administrative detail will get easer as you go along. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 1: Access the training site and this course.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto <strong>Upwork</strong> and find the contract for this job.  Start your time tracker indicate what task you are starting. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto <strong><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/\">https://MichaelKentBurns.com</a> </strong> site.   Find the Subscribe fields in the menu and subscribe yourself. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use the search field to find your name.  That should lead you to this page.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Leave a comment on this page so we know you are here.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Update time tracker to say you are done with Task 1.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Task 2:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Note the time and update time tracker to say starting task 2., </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Read the ‘Home’ page carefully down to and including ‘Working globally’ section keeping some notes along the way. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Feel free always to leave comments on any pages and posts.   It will make it easier for you and I to know you have read that page. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto <a href=\"https://demo.michaelkentburns.com/dashboard/MKB/cohort1/MKB-cohort-1-Demo\">https://demo.michaelkentburns.com/dashboard/MKB/cohort1/MKB-cohort-1-Demo</a>, select the ‘Visit the Demo-json’ button and take the ‘<strong>read-home-part1</strong>’ survey and press the ‘submission’ button.  Your answers will be captured in a json file which will appear below the ‘Submission’ button.   Finally, press the ‘Save Survey Results (JSON)’ link at the bottom.  You should then see a dialog indicating ‘Survey results saved successfully!’  Select ‘Close’.   You may also notice that the JSON file was downloaded to your downloads directory.   Save that for future reference.    Note the time and calculate how much time you have used for task 2.   Then go to the time tracker and indicate you are done with task 2 and going on to task 3.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Task 3:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Update time tracker that you are starting Task 3.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Read the ‘About’ page including the Cohort-1 ‘See full details.’ page.   When you read about Philémon, Ashuza, and Efatha, follow the links to their Github and Upwork profiles.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Take some time to study their Upwork profile.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* On Philèmon’s profile, under his picture and ‘View profile’ notice that he has two specialized profiles named&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‘Social Media Marketing’ and ‘Personal Virtual Assistance’, and finally the ‘All work’ which includes those and more.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* You will soon create your own specialized profile.&nbsp;&nbsp;Notice the ‘Portfolio’ section near the bottom of the profile.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Ashuza also has two specialized profiles: Full Stack and Mobile App.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; * Finally, notice their Certifications section.&nbsp;&nbsp;You will also get one or more certifications along the way.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Ashuza’s GitHub profile shows that he has 40 repositories!&nbsp;&nbsp;Many of them were created as he took online tutorials&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>and are fairly trivial.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* But, what is important is that they demonstrate that he not only has badges claiming knowledge of languages,&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>frameworks, and tools, he also has done a lot of visible work that shows that he spent considerable time learning.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You should remember that and make a practice of capturing all of your learning projects in your GitHub.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* We will talk more about that later.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* When you look at Efatha’s GitHub profile notice the section labeled ‘Contribution activity’.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It indicates that he has recently worked on two repositories of his own, but also the ‘MKB-cohort-1-Demo’.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; The survey app you just used is the result of their demo project.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next find yourself in Cohort-2 and read that section very carefully.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Take notes of any questions you have.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;3. Finally, to finish the ‘About’ page, read the contributors section and the pages it links to.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you get to the contributions pages notice that they have both edited or written several pages for the site.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4. Update time tracker that you have finished task 3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Then go to the survey app (Task 2, step 4) and take the ‘<strong>read-about</strong>’ survey.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Task 4:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Update time tracker as usual starting task 4.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Using the table of contents on the site, go read the ‘Front end web’ page.&nbsp;&nbsp;Read it carefully.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. As you read, make note for each section, whether you already know that information well, what you know a little bit, and what sections are new to you.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. In the areas you don’t know well, take some time to follow some of the many links provided.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Don’t study them in detail, but read enough to see what is discussed and what you may want to revisit at a later date.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. In the section about HTML and the Hello World page, take the time to actually try that for yourself.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the browser notice the address bar of your browser that the url uses the ‘<a href=\"file://\'/\">file://\'</a>&nbsp;protocol.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. When you get to the HTTP section, read that closely to understand how visiting a we page via http:// is different from file://&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;When you are done with task 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;take the survey ‘Front end web page’.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You will be asked there to relate some of the notes you talk when reading this page.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;Leave a comment at the bottom of the page and indicate something you learned on that page.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;Update time tracker to indicate you are done with task 4.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Task 5:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Read ‘Back end web’ page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Task 6:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Read ‘Full stack’ page.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Task 7:&nbsp;&nbsp;Read ‘Work globally’ page and take the two challenges it mentions.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You should now have taken challenges 1 through 4.&nbsp;&nbsp;If not, then do so now.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Cohort-2','','inherit','closed','closed','','509-revision-v1','','','2024-07-02 16:00:17','2024-07-02 16:00:17','',509,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=510',0,'revision','',0),
(512,1,'2024-07-02 16:07:20','2024-07-02 16:07:20','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Introductions</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">You are not alone in this.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will be engaging not only the material, but you will have a <strong>mentor</strong> who has been through the course.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For this course, we anticipate this pairing:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Efatha will mentor Salomon</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Philemon will mentor Gauthier</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ashuza will mentor Samuel</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>And Michael will mentor Theophile.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Starting Course</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The starting course is designed to familiarize the student with the training website and the people and processes involved.   By the end of this course you will know what is on the site and where to find what you are looking for.  You will gain a high level overview of the training you can expect from this site.  You will also know how to interact with the material, track your progress and get the help you need on your training journey.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each <strong>course</strong> is composed of a series of <strong>tasks</strong>.  These are like lessons in most learning sites but here we call them tasks because they prepare you to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Know some new technology and skill</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Give you the tools and environment to try it out for yourself</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Demonstrate your new skill</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>And finally to get some feedback about it which will guide your future learning.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The coordination of doing these tasks while using Upwork time tracker, taking surveys, and tracking hours for these steps is pretty tricky.  I’m sorry about that, but these things need to be done.   While our process includes lots of communication tools, we must continue to be consistent with the <strong>Upwork</strong> process which is important for accountability for both the client and the talent.   You need to learn this skill well if you want to engage other clients, which is the purpose of this training.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you get confused or can’t follow a specific step, please use the <strong>Upwork</strong> message system to let me know so I, or your mentor, can walk you through it.     This administrative detail will get easer as you go along. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 1: Access the training site and this course.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto <strong>Upwork</strong> and find the contract for this job.  Start your time tracker indicate what task you are starting. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto <strong><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/\">https://MichaelKentBurns.com</a> </strong> site.   Find the Subscribe fields in the menu and subscribe yourself. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use the search field to find your name.  That should lead you to this page (and possibly others).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Leave a comment on this page so we know you are here.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Update time tracker to say you are done with Task 1.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Task 2: Read the main ‘Home’ page to see your journey.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Note the time and update Upwork time tracker to say starting task 2., </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Read the ‘<strong>Home</strong>’ page carefully down to and including ‘<strong>Working globally’</strong> section keeping some notes along the way.  (There will be a quiz)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Feel free always to leave comments on any pages and posts.   It will make it easier for you and I to know you have read that page. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Goto <a href=\"https://demo.michaelkentburns.com/dashboard/MKB/cohort1/MKB-cohort-1-Demo\">https://demo.michaelkentburns.com/dashboard/MKB/cohort1/MKB-cohort-1-Demo</a>, select the ‘<strong>Visit the Demo-json</strong>’ button and take the ‘<strong>read-home-part1</strong>’ survey and press the ‘<strong>submission</strong>’ button.  Your answers will be captured in a json file which will appear below the ‘<strong>Submission</strong>’ button.   Finally, press the ‘<strong>Save Survey Results (JSON)</strong>’ link at the bottom.  You should then see a dialog indicating ‘<strong>Survey results saved successfully!</strong>’  Select ‘<strong>Close</strong>’.   You may also notice that the JSON file was downloaded to your downloads directory.   Save that for future reference.    Note the time and calculate how much time you have used for task 2.   Then go to the time tracker and indicate you are done with task 2 and going on to task 3.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Task 3:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Update time tracker that you are starting Task 3.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Read the ‘About’ page including the Cohort-1 ‘See full details.’ page.   When you read about Philémon, Ashuza, and Efatha, follow the links to their Github and Upwork profiles.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Take some time to study their Upwork profile.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* On Philèmon’s profile, under his picture and ‘View profile’ notice that he has two specialized profiles named&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‘Social Media Marketing’ and ‘Personal Virtual Assistance’, and finally the ‘All work’ which includes those and more.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* You will soon create your own specialized profile.&nbsp;&nbsp;Notice the ‘Portfolio’ section near the bottom of the profile.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Ashuza also has two specialized profiles: Full Stack and Mobile App.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; * Finally, notice their Certifications section.&nbsp;&nbsp;You will also get one or more certifications along the way.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* Ashuza’s GitHub profile shows that he has 40 repositories!&nbsp;&nbsp;Many of them were created as he took online tutorials&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>and are fairly trivial.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* But, what is important is that they demonstrate that he not only has badges claiming knowledge of languages,&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>frameworks, and tools, he also has done a lot of visible work that shows that he spent considerable time learning.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You should remember that and make a practice of capturing all of your learning projects in your GitHub.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* We will talk more about that later.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* When you look at Efatha’s GitHub profile notice the section labeled ‘Contribution activity’.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It indicates that he has recently worked on two repositories of his own, but also the ‘MKB-cohort-1-Demo’.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; The survey app you just used is the result of their demo project.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next find yourself in Cohort-2 and read that section very carefully.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Take notes of any questions you have.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;3. Finally, to finish the ‘About’ page, read the contributors section and the pages it links to.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you get to the contributions pages notice that they have both edited or written several pages for the site.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4. Update time tracker that you have finished task 3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Then go to the survey app (Task 2, step 4) and take the ‘<strong>read-about</strong>’ survey.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Task 4:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Update time tracker as usual starting task 4.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Using the table of contents